Description: CVE-2025-10911 - use-after-free via cached Result Tree Fragment linked lists
 A use-after-free vulnerability was found in libxslt while parsing xsl
 nodes that may lead to the dereference of expired pointers and
 application crash. Result Tree Fragments (RVTs) were cached in linked
 lists (cache, tmp, persist, local) that reused xmlDoc's own prev/next
 pointers for bookkeeping. Because these pointers are part of the
 standard libxml2 document/node structure, XPath evaluations could
 inadvertently traverse them and access or free RVTs that were still
 internal cache bookkeeping, leading to use of already-freed memory.
 .
 This patch introduces a dedicated xsltRVTList linked-list node type
 (containing an xmlDocPtr RVT and a next pointer) and switches every
 cache/tmp/persist/local RVT list in xsltTransformCache and
 xsltTransformContext to use it instead of reusing xmlDoc's prev/next
 fields. A new xsltReleaseRVTList() helper is added alongside the
 existing xsltReleaseRVT() (kept for ABI/API compatibility) so callers
 that already hold a list node can release it without an extra
 allocation.
